China's growing ranks of rural entrepreneurs are getting rich peddling their produce on social media.

node.text:
In almost every way measurable, millennials in the U.S. at 40 are doing worse financially than the generations that came before them.

Fewer millennials own homes than their parents did at their age. They have more debt — especially student debt. They simply aren’t as wealthy. 

Now, if predictions of a long, post-Covid economic boom are to be believed, this may be the last opportunity an entire generation has to build wealth before heading off into retirement.

node.title: Millennials Are Running Out of Time to Build Wealth to Retire

node.text:
Taiwan is becoming a bigger issue between the world's two biggest superpowers. Taipei — a U.S. ally — and Beijing have avoided war for more than seven decades, but that balance is getting harder to maintain as China becomes more assertive in its desire for reunification.

Watch the full video at the link in bio to understand why analysts say Taiwan's status is "the most likely issue to draw China and the U.S. into a direct military conflict."

node.text:
The spread of the delta variant means well over 80% of the population must have protection from the coronavirus to achieve herd immunity, according to an Infectious Diseases Society of America briefing.
 
Experts say delta's increased transmissibility has shifted the goalposts, raising the threshold to as many as 90% of people needing vaccination or immunity from a past infection to protect the broader population and reduce transmission. 
 
Previous estimates, based on earlier versions of the virus, had put the threshold between 60% and 70%. More at the link in bio.

node.text:
Turns out even the most compliant Chinese billionaires aren’t immune to the regulatory onslaught sweeping the world’s second-largest economy.

Tencent’s boss, Pony Ma, has lost more paper wealth over the past nine months than Jack Ma of Alibaba.

The loss underscores how rapidly Beijing’s crackdown has expanded. What initially looked like a targeted campaign against Ant has since spread to nearly every corner of the industry and beyond. Tap the link in bio to read more about Tencent's fall.

node.text:
A new survey shows 65% of workers who said their jobs could be done entirely remotely were willing to take a 5% reduction to stay at home.

After more than a year of full or partial remote work in many white-collar industries, employers are trying to get workers back to the office. But some workers aren’t too fond of the project — whether they are concerned about their health, have domestic responsibilities that keep them home or simply don’t want to return to an unwelcome commute.

Read more about the findings at the link in our bio.

New York City is mandating vaccines for workers and customers at gyms and indoor restaurants.
 
The city is taking a page from vaccine mandates in France and Italy, where officials have turned to restrictions on indoor activities to incentivize residents to get vaccinated. 

Mayor Bill De Blasio is focusing on requirements for vaccines, rather than masks, to deal with delta. The mayor has stopped short of mandating masks in indoor places for vaccinated residents, saying he wants to preserve an incentive for people to get their shots. Read more in our link in bio.

TikTok has been testing out a feature that allows users to submit video resumes to employers. Is it a good way to match candidates with jobs?
 
Some users undoubtedly saw TikTok Resumes as an exciting opportunity to leverage their social media skills in a challenging job market. A host of companies, including Alo and Sweetgreen, used the feature to find talent before the trial ended on July 31.

But there are lawyers and recruiters who say it adversely affects certain groups, particularly those on low incomes without access to high-end phones or glamorous backdrops. Critics also argue it could be problematic for employers striving for more inclusive hiring processes.

The ranks of Australia's richest have two new members: Nick Molnar and Anthony Eisen.
 
The co-founders of Afterpay each saw the value of their holdings soar to $1.8 billion after agreeing to sell the buy-now-pay-later business to Square, Jack Dorsey’s digital payments platform.

Molnar, 31, launched the firm seven years ago after running a "side hustle" selling jewelry on EBay. Eisen, Molnar's former neighbor, spearheaded the negotiations with Square. Tap the link in our bio for more on how they became two of the wealthiest people in Australia.

node.text:
For years, Falguni Nayar guided the founders of Indian companies through roadshows in Europe and the U.S. as they made their way to stock market debuts. Now the former investment banker is steering her own startup to an historic IPO.

Nykaa, her brainchild, has grown into India's top e-commerce site for beauty products, with the endorsement of Bollywood stars and a loyal following among twenty-somethings. Late Monday the startup filed preliminary documents for an IPO, which could value the business at more than $4 billion.

If the IPO goes as planned, Nykaa will be India's first women-led unicorn to go public — and her family’s stake stands to exceed $2 billion if it hits initial projections. Tap the link in our bio for more.

node.text:
Record numbers of Londoners are fleeing for the suburbs, even as the capital reopens and attempts to shrug off the pandemic.

The city's residents snapped up more than 60,000 homes elsewhere in the U.K. in the first six months of this year, according to Hamptons — easily the most since the broker started tracking the data 15 years ago.

The average distance from London of homes bought by former residents was 34.6 miles (55.7 kilometers), also the longest since Hamptons’ records began. Tap the link in bio for more on wear they’re heading.

node.text:
Goldman has raised pay for its junior investment bankers, becoming the last of the big Wall Street banks to boost wages after a presentation by the lender's own analysts revealing their crushing workloads.

First-year analysts at Goldman will now earn at least $110,000, according to people familiar with the matter. Their second-year counterparts will earn $125,000. 

The move aligns Goldman with Morgan Stanley, Citigroup and JPMorgan, which all bumped starting wages for junior banking employees to $100,000 to prevent defections sparked by their intense workloads. Tap the link in our bio for more.
